 ],
 "whyMissable": "Colocation reads as the segment where rack PDUs are structurally mandatory (per-rack metering, multi-tenant billing), and the node's null band means it never surfaces in any sensitivity view — the team's eyes are drawn to banded nodes. The kill path runs through the wholesale/retail split inside the 18%, a distinction the model does not carry at all.",
 "falsifier": "Fit-out specifications from 2026 CE wholesale colocation preleases (Frankfurt, Amsterdam) showing rack PDUs — tenant-supplied or operator-supplied — as the standard rack power distribution in AI-density halls rather than busway/shelf architectures.",
 "likelihoodRationale": "Tenant spec authority in wholesale preleases is well documented and the buyer cohort is verifiably the migrating one, but retail colo and standard-density wholesale (the majority of current CE colo MW) remain PDU-native; the risk concentrates in the AI-density prelet growth tranche within the 12-month window [evidence revision: External evidence firmly confirms the trigger (buyer cohort, wholesale single-let dominance, capacity growth) and shows busway/power-shelf systems are explicitly marketed and deployed for AI-density colo white space, tightening the propagation link. However, the CBRE data also complicates the geographic concentration — the AI signing surge is heavily Nordic (57%) rather than Frankfurt/Amsterdam, and no direct CE prelease fit-out spec was found to confirm PDU displacement in the exact falsifier markets. Retail colo remains PDU-native (JMP/Digital Realty). Net modest upward revision from 0.30 to 0.34 within the 12-month window.]"
